{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2011}}
'''Phiona Mutesi''' is a [[Uganda]]n [[chess]] player.<ref name="autogenerated1">{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/news/story?id=5965666 |title=ESPN the Magazine NEXT <U+2013> Meet chess progidy Phiona Mutesi <U+2013> ESPN |publisher=ESPN  |date=4 January 2011 |accessdate=10 November 2011}}</ref> She is not certain when she was born, although [[FIDE]] has estimated it to be 1993.<ref name="autogenerated1"/><ref>{{fide|id=10000399}}</ref> She grew up in the Ugandan slum of [[Katwe]], where as of 2011 fifty percent of teen girls were mothers; when Phiona was about three her father died of [[AIDS]] and shortly afterwards her older sister Juliet died of an unknown cause.<ref name="autogenerated1"/> When Phiona was about nine, and had already dropped out of school as her family could not afford to send her, she found a chess program run by the Sports Outreach Institute, which taught her how to play chess.<ref name="autogenerated1"/> In 2010 she played on board 2 for Uganda at the [[39th Chess Olympiad]], and as of 2011 she was a three-time Women's Junior Champion of Uganda.<ref name="chessgames1">{{cite web|url=http://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessplayer?pid=127569&kpage=1#reply3 |title=The chess games of Phiona Mutesi |publisher=Chessgames.com |accessdate=10 November 2011}}</ref><ref name="chessgames1"/> In 2012, Phiona and Ivy Amoko earned [[Woman Candidate Master]] (WCM) titles as a result of their performances at the  [[40th Chess Olympiad]], making them the first titled female players in Ugandan chess history.<ref>http://www.kawowo.com/index.php/chess/2149-uganda-gets-titled-players-at-world-chess-olympiad.html</ref><ref>http://www.kawowo.com/index.php/chess/2158-wanyama-becomes-fide-master.html</ref><ref>[http://ugandadailyeye.jibostudios.com/?p=9631 Mutesi, Amoko set to become Candidate Masters<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> That same year Phiona became the first female player to win the open category of the National Junior Chess Championship in Uganda.<ref>[http://uganda.fide.com/component/content/article/2-news/116-mutesi-wins-national-junior-chess-championship MUTESI WINS 2012 NATIONAL JUNIOR CHESS CHAMPIONSHIP<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Also in 2012, a book was published about Phiona titled, "The Queen of Katwe: A Story of Life, Chess, and One Extraordinary Girl's Dream of Becoming a Grandmaster", by [[Tim Crothers]].<ref>[http://www.amazon.com/The-Queen-Katwe-Extraordinary-Grandmaster/dp/1451657811/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&qid=1351551869&sr=8-1&keywords=queen+of+katwe The Queen of Katwe: A Story of Life, Chess, and One Extraordinary Girl's Dream of Becoming a Grandmaster: Tim Crothers: 9781451657814: Amazon.com: Books<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> Disney has optioned the rights to the book, and is starting work on a movie as of 2012.<ref name=autogenerated2>http://www.cnn.com/2012/12/10/world/africa/uganda-chess-teen/index.html?hpt=hp_c1</ref> There is also a documentary about Phiona on YouTube.<ref name=autogenerated2 />

Phiona is also the youngest person ever to win the African chess championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsoutreach.net/phiona.html |title=Queen of Katwe! |publisher=Sportsoutreach.net |accessdate=10 November 2011}}</ref>

